{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2450"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2450"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.43,0.06,0.42,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101965"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2450"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"404"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15924"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43156"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101965"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after falling at home and sustaining a right neck of femur fracture. She was previously independent at home. On further history, it appears the fall was mechanical, as she slipped on a mat while doing laundry. She did not recently stand up prior to falling, and she did not lose consciousness or have any palpitations or shortness of breath before falling. She has a medical history of hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, mild cognitive impairment, and angina. Her medications include glyceryl trinitrate as needed, ramipril, rosuvastatin, and aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe subsequently undergoes a right total hip arthroplasty. She is recovering well with rehabilitation and is medically cleared for discharge. Investigations in hospital show that she has a haemoglobin of 135 g/L (125 \u2013 160), and her vitamin D level is low.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following single interventions is considered the most important in reducing falls risk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vitamin D supplementation","Strength and balance training exercises","Bisphosphonate therapy","Home safety assessment and modification","Tai Chi classes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe single most effective intervention to reduce falls risk is \u003Cstrong\u003Estrength and balance training exercises\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient would benefit from a structured exercise program that focuses on improving muscle strength, balance, and coordination. Such exercises have been shown to significantly reduce the risk of falls in older adults, particularly those with a history of falls or fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is warranted if she is found to have low vitamin D levels; however, it is unlikely to reduce her risk of falling significantly, though it may reduce her risk of sustaining fractures from low-impact falls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisphosphonate therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate for the treatment of osteoporosis and is also warranted in this patient (after correcting vitamin D levels) given her age and neck of femur fracture; however, it is unlikely to reduce her risk of falls. Bisphosphonates primarily work by increasing bone density and reducing fracture risk, not by preventing falls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHome safety assessment and modification\u003C/strong\u003E is an important intervention for reducing falls risk, especially given that this patient\u0027s fall occurred at home due to a hazard (slipping on a mat). This could involve removing tripping hazards, improving lighting, installing handrails, and other environmental modifications. While this is valuable, it is not as consistently effective as strength and balance training in reducing falls risk across various settings, particularly given requirement for these exercises as part of rehabilitation process. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETai Chi classes\u003C/strong\u003E can be beneficial for improving balance and reducing falls risk in older adults. However, while Tai Chi is a form of exercise that incorporates balance and strength components, it is not as comprehensive or as widely studied as structured strength and balance training programs. Additionally, Tai Chi may not be suitable for all patients, particularly those recovering from recent surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, while all of these interventions can play a role in a comprehensive falls prevention strategy, strength and balance training exercises have the strongest evidence base for reducing falls risk in older adults and should be prioritized in this patient\u0027s care plan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The single most effective intervention to reduce falls risk is strength and balance training.","Home safety assessment and modification can significantly reduce falls risk in older adults.","Recommendation for all adults post hip fracture to participate in progressive and individualised exercise program to help improve mobility and prevent further falls"],"references":["Phelan EA, Mahoney JE, Voit JC, Stevens JA. Assessment and management of fall risk in primary care settings. Med Clin North Am. 2015;99(2):281-93. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4707663/","Montero-Odasso M, van der Velde N, Martin FC, et al. World guidelines for falls prevention and management for older adults: a global initiative [published correction appears in Age Ageing. 2023 Sep 1;52(9):afad188. doi: 10.1093/ageing/afad188] [published correction appears in Age Ageing. 2023 Oct 2;52(10):afad199. doi: 10.1093/ageing/afad199]. Age Ageing. 2022;51(9):afac205. doi:10.1093/ageing/afac205"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2450"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-05T18:53:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-05T18:53:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2450"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101965"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"ty